    <!-- Opportunity Summary -->
    <section class="section">
        <div class="section-label">Opportunity Summary</div>
        <h2 class="section-headline">Everyone is racing to build AI agents.<br>No one is building the personal data layer they all need.</h2>
        <div class="section-body">
            <p>Personal agentic computing is the defining shift in how people interact with technology. OpenClaw, Claude Cowork, ZoComputer, Perplexity Computer, Manus — over 100 million people already pay $20+/month for AI. The agentic AI market is projected to exceed <strong>$50B by 2030</strong> at a 44% CAGR.</p>
            <p>But features get cloned in weeks. It's a race to the bottom backed by billions of dollars. And despite all this investment, every platform's memory is shallow — basically one big text file. It remembers your name, not six months of your thinking. There's no structured knowledge about your projects, your people, your patterns over time.</p>
            <p>There's a deeper problem upstream: <em>how</em> your thinking gets into the system. You can talk to your AI, but that's a conversation — the AI is always in the middle. There's no good way to think for yourself, capture that thinking naturally, and have it become context that makes your AI better. Tools that help us think for ourselves — not just think <em>with</em> AI — produce the quality of thinking that makes AI most useful.</p>
            <p>Parachute solves both problems. <strong>Parachute Daily</strong> is a voice-first journaling app that makes it effortless to capture your thinking — on a walk, in the car, wherever it happens. Under the hood, those notes live in a graph database that any AI can access via MCP (Model Context Protocol). You don't switch AI tools. You add Parachute — and whatever AI you already use gets dramatically better.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Product or Service -->
    <section class="section">
        <div class="section-label">Product or Service</div>
        <h2 class="section-headline">Simple for humans.<br>Native for AI.</h2>
        <div class="section-body">
            <p><strong>Parachute Daily</strong> is the first product. Users speak into a wearable pendant or their phone. Entries are transcribed (offline-capable via on-device models), organized, and structured. It works fully offline as a simple journal for free; cloud sync and MCP access unlock at $2/month, cloud transcription at $5/month, and AI features (reflections, vector search, synthesis) at $10/month.</p>
            <p><strong>Under the hood</strong>, notes live in a graph database organized around three primitives: <strong>Things, Tags, and Tools</strong>. This architecture is deliberately simple but powerful. A journal entry is a Thing tagged as "daily note." A person mentioned in your journals can be a Thing tagged as "person" with linked contact info. A project is a Thing with linked tasks and notes. The graph grows organically from your natural thinking.</p>
            <p>Because the system speaks MCP, any AI agent can read, search, and even create structure in your graph. Your AI can scan journals and generate people nodes, project nodes, link them together, pull in contact info. Your notes become a <strong>living knowledge graph</strong> — and the more structure it has, the more powerful your AI becomes, regardless of which AI you choose.</p>
            <p><strong>The Pendant</strong> is a wearable voice capture device. Press a button, talk, and by the time you're home your thoughts are transcribed and structured. Working prototype built with custom Parachute enclosure.</p>
            <p><strong>Current state:</strong> Working Python/FastAPI server, Flutter app (macOS, Android, web), graph-native storage, local voice transcription via Sherpa-ONNX, MCP server. Functional pendant prototype. Daily beta launching this month, with production launch targeted for June 2026. OpenParachute PBC incorporated in Colorado.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Competitive Differentiation -->
    <section class="section">
        <div class="section-label">Competitive Differentiation</div>
        <h2 class="section-headline">Don't compete with agents.<br>Build the tool layer they all need.</h2>
        <div class="section-body">
            <p>The personal AI space is crowded — OpenClaw, TwinMind, Mem.ai, ZoComputer, Perplexity Computer, Manus. Rather than joining the race to build another agent, Parachute differentiates by being the layer <em>underneath</em> all of them:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>Agent-native, not agent-competitive</strong> — Parachute works with whatever AI you already use via MCP. You don't switch — you add. This means every AI user is a potential customer, not just people willing to migrate.</li>
                <li><strong>Capture over conversation</strong> — Talking to your AI is a conversation. Parachute helps you think for yourself — capture your own thinking naturally, then bring AI in when you're ready. That independent thinking is what makes AI most useful.</li>
                <li><strong>Deep memory, not shallow</strong> — Not a flat text file of preferences. A real graph database that can be queried across months and years, with structured knowledge about your people, projects, and patterns.</li>
                <li><strong>Open source as trust</strong> — AGPL-3.0, local-first, data on your device. Public Benefit Corporation. The trust required for people to share their deepest thinking with a system.</li>
                <li><strong>Context compounds as the moat</strong> — Software gets cloned in a day. Months of accumulated personal context cannot. The switching cost is genuine value, not lock-in.</li>
            </ul>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Market and Customer Analysis -->
    <section class="section">
        <div class="section-label">Market & Customer Analysis</div>
        <h2 class="section-headline">Every AI user is a potential customer.</h2>
        <div class="section-body">
            <p>The agentic AI market is projected to exceed $50B by 2030 at a 44% CAGR. Over 100 million people already pay $20+/month for AI — and that number is growing rapidly. Because Parachute complements rather than competes with these tools, <strong>every one of those users is a potential customer</strong>.</p>
            <p>Adjacent comparables: TwinMind ($5.7M raised at $60M valuation), Obsidian (~$25M ARR as a note-taking tool), Day One (~$4.8M ARR as a journaling app), Mem.ai ($28.6M raised for AI-powered knowledge management).</p>
            <p>We target two overlapping segments:</p>
            <ul>
                <li><strong>AI users who want better context</strong> — People already paying for Claude, ChatGPT, or other AI tools who want their AI to actually know them. $2/month for sync + MCP access is a no-brainer addition to their existing AI subscription.</li>
                <li><strong>Non-AI users who want a great journal</strong> — People who aren't using AI yet but want a simple, voice-first way to capture their thinking. Daily gives them AI-light features that gradually open up the ecosystem. The pendant makes capture effortless.</li>
            </ul>
            <p><strong>Validation:</strong> 300+ community members in our Boulder ecosystem ready to onboard. 13 builders completed our first Learn Vibe Build AI learning cohort. Active users in private beta providing ongoing feedback.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

    <!-- IP -->
    <section class="section">
        <div class="section-label">Intellectual Property</div>
        <h2 class="section-headline">Open source is the strategy.</h2>
        <div class="section-body">
            <p>Parachute is open source under the <strong>AGPL-3.0 license</strong> — a copyleft license that requires anyone who runs a modified version as a hosted service to share their changes. This protects against proprietary forks while keeping the codebase fully transparent.</p>
            <p>Our defensible advantages are the compounding user context (which lives with each user and grows over time), the graph database architecture (Things, Tags, Tools), the MCP integration layer, the community ecosystem, and the trust earned by building in the open. Open source is a competitive advantage: it builds the trust necessary for people to share their most personal thinking with a system.</p>
        </div>
    </section>

